column36: PresbyteriansThe Awakening in American began in the middle colonies among the Presbyterians, namely in Pennsylvania and New Jersey. The leader of this movement was a pastor named William Tennent. He and his family organized religious revivals across the two colonies. They also established a school whose purpose was to train men to become clergymen and pastors. The trained clergy’s goal was to spread the work of the Tennent’s farther and farther away. The school was called “Log College” then, and it still functions today, under the name of Princeton University.
